<h2>Introduction:</h2>
This lab exercises the ability to:
<ul>
    <li>Use the division and remainder operators to solve problems.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Lab Assignment:</h2>

<ol>
    <li> Create a new directory, <b><tt>Lab5</tt></b>, in your class account directory.</li>
    <li> Move into your Lab5 directory</li>
    <li> Using a syntax-highlighting editor, open a new file to edit.  Save it as <tt><i>filename</i>.html</tt>.</li>
    <li> For each of the following tasks,</li>
    <ol>
	<li> modify your Web page file via the editor</li>
	<li> save the file</li>
	<li> refresh the browser open to your Web page</li>
	<li> verify that your modifications did what you've intended</li>
    </ol>
</ol>
Perform <i>all</i> of the requirements in each of the following Exercises in Reed:
<ol>
    <li> <u>Exercise 5.17</u> (uses 5.16)<br>
         Also, on this Web page, provide functionality in the opposite direction, i.e.
	 have the user enter
	 <u><tt>days</tt></u>,
	 <u><tt>hours</tt></u>,
	 <u><tt>minutes</tt></u>, and
	 <u><tt>seconds</tt></u><br>
	 (<i>ensure that your input to one is the output of the other</i>)
     </li>
     <li>
	Create a Webpage that prompts for a four digit non-negative decimal number then displays the number backwards.<br>
	(<i>You can do this by stripping off each digit from the right and then writing it to the page.</i>)
     </li>
</ol>
    <p>
    When finished (after you’ve proofread your Web page), submit your files to the appropriate D2L dropbox.
